post_text:
SLUSD FREE MEAL PROGRAM RETURNS BEGINNING SEPTEMBER 8!

Our free meals program for all students is back, thanks to new USDA guidelines! Just like we did all summer, we will be serving meals to all children 18 and under three days a week from our seven distribution sites starting September 8, with no barcode or proof of residency needed. Any child can get a meal from any location.

We are also expanding our service to include meals for the weekends. This means we will serve two days worth of meals on Monday and Wednesdays, and three days worth of meals on Fridays.

There will be no meal distribution on Monday, September 7 in observance of the Labor Day holiday. But there will be a special morning and midday meal distribution on Tuesday, September 8 at sites listed below.

Our service hours have also expanded, with morning pickup available from 6:30 am to 8:00 am at Monroe, Muir, and SLHS (north parking lot by library/main office)

post_text:
Wishing everyone a day of celebration in recognition of Liberation Day, also known as Juneteenth.

On June 19, 1865, federal orders were read aloud in the city of Galveston, Texas, proclaiming that all enslaved persons in that state -- the last to hold Americans in bondage -- were now free.

Many in our SLUSD community will be deepening their practice in bringing antiracist practices to our schools over the summer through a book study organized by the Educational Services department as we continue the fight for equity.

We hope your day is filled with love and a strong sense of community.

post_text:
San Leandro School Board of Education Statement on School Resource Officer Programs in SLUSD

We have received thoughtful inquiries about School Resource Officer programs in our district schools. SLUSD has not had a School Resource Officer program since the 2016-17 school year. A separate elementary school program offered by the San Leandro Police Department, referred to as Gang Resistance Education And Training (GREAT), was discontinued in 2018.

Moving forward, police officers will only be on any of our campuses in the event of an emergency or if taking a crime report.

We thank you for always providing us with your valuable feedback. We look forward to further dialogue as we work to reopen our schools with safety and equity at the forefront of our planning.

Sincerely,

The San Leandro Unified School Board of Education

Peter Oshinski, President
Evelyn Gonzalez, Vice President
Christian Rodriguez, Board Clerk
James Aguilar, Trustee
Diana Prola, Trustee
Leo Sheridan, Trustee
Monique Tate, Trustee

With today as the last day of school for San Leandro Unified, our 5th-grade promotions are complete, our 8th graders are on their way to San Leandro High School, and now we are getting ready to bid loving farewells to our Pirate Seniors! Your SLUSD School Board of Education is sending their congratulations to all of our students in the historic Class of 2020 along with a tribute to one of our favorite traditions in SLUSD, the dazzling decorated graduation caps that sadly, we won‚Äôt get to admire in person this year.

But, you can tune in tonight at 5:30 to see the SLHS virtual promotion at www.slhs.net and see for yourself why we are so proud of our Pirates. After all of our years together, we know beyond a doubt that these beautiful, brilliant souls graduating tonight will be the keys to uplifting our society and completely transforming our world.

Congratulations Class of 2020!

post_text:
We would like to be among the first, and far from the last, to wish everyone a happy San Leandro Unified Teacher Appreciation Week! The school board passed Resolution 20-15 to recognize the extremely influential work of our certificated staff. Never has this been more true than right now, as our teaching staff swiftly and fluidly navigates the many challenges of Emergency Distance Learning.

As we start our eighth week of physical distance, we offer our utmost appreciation for the sincere care being extended to our students and families. These authentic connections are a foundational reason SLUSD is such a special place to work and learn. We are fortunate to have a timely artifact of the power of teaching and learning in SLUSD in this slideshow from some of our SLHS seniors, proudly announcing where they are off to next year. Oh how much we miss these beautiful faces! Congratulations Pirates!

post_text: As this month ends, we look back at days filled with Black History school activities, like choral concerts, poetry slams, food and family gatherings, and more. We also hosted the 16th annual San Leandro High School Career Day - co-sponsored with the San Leandro African American Business Council and Chamber of Commerce, which brought a significant number of African American business leaders into our school to tell their own powerful stories. In SLUSD, celebrating Black History is a year-long event, but February is very special. Looking forward to starting March on Monday in our libraries at Reading Across America Day!

The SLHS girls basketball team plays in the North Coast Section Championship on Saturday at Dublin High School vs San Ramon Valley High School. Tip-off is 5:30 pm. They have been considered the underdogs in the last two games they played, beating the #4 seed and #1 seed in back to back games in the qualifying tournament.

The team consists of:
1 senior - Beverly Bradley
3 juniors - Mykala Pakeman, Tovaleomania Tupouata, Janessa DeFranco
5 sophomores - Monique Fischer, Jayonnah Carter, Lyndsey Marrujo, Nicolette Mailangi, and Maya Pollard
1 freshman - Geriah Bradley

Mykala Pakeman, Janessa DeFranco, and Maya Pollard all got 1st team all league as well. Tovale got 2nd team. And Mykala was also league MVP

Please join us in shouting at the top of your lungs...GO PIRATES!!

For the first time in 4 years the San Leandro High Boys Wrestling Team has qualified an athlete for the CIF State Tournament. Callan Ivy placed 3rd this past weekend by pinning the same opponent who had eliminated him from the tournament last year in the Round of 16.
We are also rooting for SLHS sophomore Kendall Branchaud, who secured her spot in the CIF State Tournament once again with a 4th Place finish at the NCS Tournament!

They will be competing at Rabobank Arena in Bakersfield, CA at the 3-Day State Tournament. Kendall will start competition Thursday at 9 am and Callan will start at 1pm. GO PIRATES!!

Last night was also the 1st annual English Language Development (ELD) and World Languages Talent Showcase at San Leandro High School.

All student performers were bilingual or multilingual, fluent in Spanish, Tigrinya, Vietnamese, Tagalog, various dialects from the Philippines, various dialects of Chinese, and more!

We are so fortunate to have 38 languages are spoken in SLUSD schools, which brings the priceless gift of diversity to all of our students.
